if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_oesophagus']=[
  {q:"The anatomical constriction of the esophagus most relevant during rigid esophagoscopy at the level of the cricopharyngeus is located approximately:",o:["5 cm from incisors","10 cm from incisors","15 cm from incisors","25 cm from incisors","40 cm from incisors"],a:2,e:"The upper esophageal constriction at the cricopharyngeus lies approximately 15 cm from the upper incisors and is the narrowest part of the adult esophagus.<br><br>This region is clinically important because impacted foreign bodies commonly lodge here during ENT emergencies. It is also the commonest site of iatrogenic perforation during rigid esophagoscopy.<br><br>The lower measurements correspond to thoracic and gastroesophageal constrictions rather than the cricopharyngeal region.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing thyroidectomy develops postoperative dysphagia and aspiration. Injury to which nerve most likely impaired upper esophageal sphincter coordination?",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Trigeminal nerve"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve supplies the cricopharyngeus and contributes significantly to upper esophageal sphincter coordination during swallowing. Injury disrupts pharyngoesophageal function.<br><br>Patients may develop aspiration, pooling of secretions, dysphagia, and ineffective airway protection after surgery involving the thyroid or tracheoesophageal groove.<br><br>Facial (A), lingual (D), and trigeminal nerves (E) are less directly involved in upper esophageal sphincter control.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The upper esophageal sphincter is formed primarily by the:",o:["Thyrohyoid muscle","Sternohyoid muscle","Cricopharyngeus muscle","Inferior constrictor only","Stylopharyngeus muscle"],a:2,e:"The cricopharyngeus forms the major component of the upper esophageal sphincter and remains tonically contracted at rest to prevent air entry into the esophagus.<br><br>Failure of relaxation during swallowing contributes to dysphagia and disorders such as cricopharyngeal spasm and Zenker diverticulum formation.<br><br>Inferior constrictor fibers (D) contribute partially, but the cricopharyngeus is the principal sphincteric component.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with progressive dysphagia, regurgitation of undigested food, halitosis, and nocturnal cough. The pathology most likely arises through Killian dehiscence located between:",o:["Superior and middle constrictors","Thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus","Cricopharyngeus and cervical esophagus","Stylopharyngeus and salpingopharyngeus","Thyrohyoid and sternohyoid muscles"],a:1,e:"Zenker diverticulum develops through Killian dehiscence, a weak area between oblique thyropharyngeus and transverse cricopharyngeus fibers of the inferior constrictor.<br><br>Patients commonly present with dysphagia, regurgitation, aspiration, gurgling neck swelling, and halitosis due to food retention within the pouch.<br><br>The remaining anatomical relationships are unrelated to formation of pharyngoesophageal diverticula.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During rigid esophagoscopy, the structure most vulnerable to perforation at the upper constriction is the:",o:["Posterior pharyngeal wall","Pyriform fossa","Cricopharyngeal region","Vallecula","Base of tongue"],a:2,e:"The cricopharyngeal narrowing represents the narrowest and least distensible portion of the esophagus. Instrumentation here requires careful technique during rigid esophagoscopy.<br><br>Perforation may result in mediastinitis, cervical emphysema, fever, and severe neck pain, making it one of the most feared ENT endoscopic complications.<br><br>Vallecula (D) and pyriform fossa (B) are important landmarks but are not the usual perforation sites during esophagoscopy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old man complains of progressive dysphagia first to solids and later to liquids, associated with weight loss and hoarseness. Left vocal cord paralysis is detected on laryngoscopy. Which anatomical relationship explains the vocal cord paralysis?",o:["Compression of hypoglossal nerve","Injury to superior laryngeal artery","Involvement of recurrent laryngeal nerve","Compression of glossopharyngeal nerve","Involvement of facial nerve"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove, making it vulnerable to compression or invasion by esophageal malignancies.<br><br>Patients may develop hoarseness due to unilateral vocal cord paralysis, often indicating advanced local disease with poorer prognosis.<br><br>Hypoglossal (A) and facial nerves (E) do not lie in close relation to the cervical esophagus.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The normal physiological function of the upper esophageal sphincter includes prevention of:",o:["Gastric acid secretion","Peristalsis within esophagus","Air entry into esophagus during respiration","Salivary secretion","Lower esophageal relaxation"],a:2,e:"The upper esophageal sphincter remains tonically contracted between swallows, preventing aerophagia and reflux of esophageal contents into the pharynx.<br><br>During swallowing, coordinated relaxation allows smooth passage of the food bolus into the cervical esophagus while simultaneously protecting the airway.<br><br>Peristalsis (C) and gastric acid secretion (A) are unrelated primary functions of the upper esophageal sphincter.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cricopharyngeal dysfunction is most likely to complain of:",o:["Nasal obstruction only","Conductive hearing loss","Oropharyngeal dysphagia","Facial numbness","Vertigo"],a:2,e:"Failure of appropriate cricopharyngeal relaxation impairs bolus transfer from pharynx into esophagus. Patients therefore commonly complain of difficulty initiating swallowing.<br><br>Pooling of secretions, aspiration, coughing during meals, and sensation of food sticking in the neck are additional common symptoms.<br><br>Hearing loss (C), vertigo (E), and facial numbness (D) are unrelated to cricopharyngeal disorders.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The cervical esophagus begins anatomically at the level of the:",o:["Hyoid bone","C3 vertebra","Lower border of cricoid cartilage","Thyroid notch","Suprasternal notch"],a:2,e:"The esophagus begins at the lower border of the cricoid cartilage opposite the C6 vertebral level, continuing inferiorly from the pharynx.<br><br>This anatomical landmark is highly important during tracheostomy, thyroid surgery, and rigid endoscopy because of the close relationship between airway and esophagus.<br><br>The hyoid bone (A) and thyroid notch (D) lie superior to the true pharyngoesophageal junction.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with drooling, dysphagia, and inability to swallow saliva after accidentally ingesting a coin. The most common site of foreign body impaction is:",o:["Lower esophageal sphincter","Mid-thoracic esophagus","Cricopharyngeal narrowing","Gastroesophageal junction","Pyriform sinus"],a:2,e:"The upper esophageal constriction at the cricopharyngeus is the narrowest part of the esophagus and therefore the commonest site of foreign body impaction.<br><br>Children commonly present with drooling, dysphagia, neck discomfort, and refusal to eat after accidental ingestion of coins or similar objects.<br><br>Lower constrictions (A, D) are less common sites of impaction in pediatric ENT emergencies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The arterial supply of the cervical esophagus is derived mainly from branches of the:",o:["Facial artery","Lingual artery","Inferior thyroid artery","Maxillary artery","Occipital artery"],a:2,e:"The cervical esophagus receives arterial blood mainly from branches of the inferior thyroid artery, which also supplies adjacent laryngeal and thyroid structures.<br><br>Knowledge of this vascular anatomy is important during neck surgery because esophageal ischemia and fistula formation may complicate extensive operative procedures.<br><br>Facial (A) and maxillary arteries (D) primarily supply structures of the face and oral cavity.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal perforation after rigid esophagoscopy develops severe neck pain, fever, and crepitus. The crepitus occurs because of:",o:["Vocal cord edema","Air leakage into cervical fascial planes","Tracheal calcification","Superior laryngeal nerve injury","Thyroid enlargement"],a:1,e:"Perforation allows air and saliva to escape into surrounding soft tissues, producing cervical emphysema and palpable crepitus. Mediastinitis may rapidly follow if untreated.<br><br>Patients require urgent recognition and management because delayed treatment markedly increases morbidity and mortality.<br><br>Tracheal calcification (C) and thyroid enlargement (E) do not produce acute surgical emphysema after esophageal instrumentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscular wall of the upper third of the esophagus consists predominantly of:",o:["Smooth muscle only","Cardiac muscle","Skeletal muscle","Mixed smooth and cardiac muscle","Fibrous tissue only"],a:2,e:"The upper third of the esophagus contains predominantly striated skeletal muscle, allowing voluntary initiation of swallowing. The lower esophagus transitions gradually into smooth muscle.<br><br>This arrangement explains why neurological disorders affecting voluntary musculature commonly produce oropharyngeal dysphagia rather than distal esophageal symptoms initially.<br><br>Smooth muscle predominates mainly in the distal esophagus rather than the cervical portion.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing gastroesophageal reflux develops chronic laryngitis and hoarseness. Which mechanism most directly explains the laryngeal symptoms?",o:["Trigeminal irritation","Facial nerve compression","Direct acid exposure to laryngeal mucosa","Increased salivary secretion","Conductive hearing loss"],a:2,e:"Laryngopharyngeal reflux exposes delicate laryngeal mucosa to gastric acid and pepsin, causing edema, inflammation, and chronic irritation.<br><br>Patients frequently present to ENT clinics with hoarseness, throat clearing, globus sensation, chronic cough, and posterior laryngitis rather than classic heartburn alone.<br><br>Facial nerve compression (B) and trigeminal irritation (C) do not explain reflux-associated laryngeal disease.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old edentulous patient develops progressive dysphagia and regurgitation of undigested food several hours after eating. Examination reveals gurgling in the lower neck. Which condition is most likely?",o:["Achalasia cardia","Zenker diverticulum","Esophageal varices","Plummer-Vinson syndrome","Retropharyngeal abscess"],a:1,e:"Zenker diverticulum is a pulsion diverticulum arising through Killian dehiscence due to cricopharyngeal dysfunction. Food retention within the pouch causes regurgitation and halitosis.<br><br>Patients may additionally develop aspiration pneumonia, chronic cough, and a characteristic gurgling cervical swelling during swallowing.<br><br>Achalasia (A) affects the lower esophageal sphincter rather than the pharyngoesophageal junction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During swallowing, relaxation of the upper esophageal sphincter is coordinated mainly by the:",o:["Medullary swallowing center","Cerebellum only","Basal ganglia exclusively","Facial nucleus","Cochlear nucleus"],a:0,e:"Swallowing is coordinated by complex neural circuits within the medulla that synchronize pharyngeal contraction, laryngeal elevation, and cricopharyngeal relaxation.<br><br>Neurological disorders affecting these pathways commonly produce aspiration and severe oropharyngeal dysphagia requiring multidisciplinary management.<br><br>The cerebellum (B) contributes to coordination but does not independently control the swallowing reflex.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The weakest area in the posterior pharyngeal wall predisposing to Zenker diverticulum formation is called:",o:["Broyles ligament","Killian dehiscence","Rouviere sinus","Rosenmüller fossa","Cricotracheal membrane"],a:1,e:"Killian dehiscence is a triangular weak area between fibers of thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus muscles. Increased intrapharyngeal pressure may force mucosa through this region.<br><br>This results in pulsion diverticulum formation with characteristic symptoms of dysphagia, regurgitation, and aspiration.<br><br>Broyles ligament (A) is related to the anterior commissure of the larynx rather than the pharyngoesophageal junction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with upper esophageal carcinoma most likely presents initially with:",o:["Conductive hearing loss","Facial palsy","Progressive dysphagia","Severe vertigo","Nasal obstruction"],a:2,e:"Esophageal malignancy typically presents with gradually progressive dysphagia, initially affecting solids and later liquids as luminal narrowing increases.<br><br>Weight loss, odynophagia, aspiration, and recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy may develop with advancing disease.<br><br>Vertigo (D), hearing loss (A), and facial palsy (C) are unrelated presenting features.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends in close relation to the:",o:["Carotid sheath only","Stylomandibular ligament","Tracheoesophageal groove","Parotid fascia","Submandibular triangle"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove before entering the larynx. This relationship is highly important surgically.<br><br>Esophageal tumors, thyroid surgery, and cervical lymphadenopathy may therefore produce recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy with resulting hoarseness.<br><br>The nerve does not normally course within the parotid fascia (D) or submandibular triangle (E).<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe cricopharyngeal spasm may benefit surgically from:",o:["Septoplasty","Cricopharyngeal myotomy","Mastoidectomy","Tympanoplasty","Functional endoscopic sinus surgery"],a:1,e:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy divides the dysfunctional upper esophageal sphincter muscle, improving bolus passage into the esophagus.<br><br>The procedure is particularly useful in selected patients with cricopharyngeal achalasia, neuromuscular dysphagia, and Zenker diverticulum.<br><br>Septoplasty (A) and mastoidectomy (C) are unrelated ENT procedures.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops aspiration pneumonia secondary to pharyngoesophageal dysfunction. Which protective mechanism normally prevents aspiration during swallowing?",o:["Vocal cord abduction","Opening of eustachian tube","Coordinated laryngeal elevation and glottic closure","Nasal septal movement","Tympanic membrane retraction"],a:2,e:"During swallowing, the larynx elevates while the vocal cords adduct and epiglottis retroflexes, protecting the airway from aspiration.<br><br>Failure of these coordinated events due to neurological or structural disease predisposes to aspiration, coughing, and recurrent chest infections.<br><br>Vocal cord abduction (A) actually widens the airway and would increase aspiration risk during swallowing.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The physiological peristaltic movement of the esophagus is controlled predominantly by the:",o:["Enteric and vagal nervous systems","Facial nerve only","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve exclusively","Optic nerve"],a:0,e:"Esophageal peristalsis depends upon coordinated neural control involving vagal innervation and the enteric nervous system. This allows orderly propulsion of swallowed material.<br><br>Disruption of these mechanisms contributes to motility disorders such as achalasia and diffuse esophageal spasm.<br><br>Vestibulocochlear (C) and optic nerves (E) have no role in esophageal motility.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing iron deficiency anemia develops dysphagia due to upper esophageal webs. This condition is known as:",o:["Mallory-Weiss syndrome","Plummer-Vinson syndrome","Boerhaave syndrome","Barrett esophagus","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome"],a:1,e:"Plummer-Vinson syndrome consists of iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia, and upper esophageal webs. It carries increased risk of postcricoid carcinoma.<br><br>Patients may additionally exhibit glossitis, koilonychia, and angular cheilitis. ENT surveillance is important because of malignant potential.<br><br>Boerhaave syndrome (C) refers to spontaneous esophageal rupture rather than esophageal webs.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cervical esophageal perforation after foreign body removal develops mediastinitis because the cervical fascial planes:",o:["Prevent downward spread of infection","Are lined completely by cartilage","Communicate directly with mediastinum","Contain no vascular structures","Prevent air tracking"],a:2,e:"Deep cervical fascial planes communicate freely with the superior mediastinum, allowing rapid spread of infection and air after esophageal perforation.<br><br>Mediastinitis is therefore a life-threatening complication requiring prompt recognition, antibiotics, drainage, and supportive care.<br><br>The fascial planes do not prevent spread (A) and certainly allow air tracking into cervical tissues.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing rigid esophagoscopy is positioned with neck extension primarily to:",o:["Reduce middle ear pressure","Improve nasal airflow","Align oral cavity, pharynx, and esophagus","Prevent vocal cord vibration","Increase salivary secretion"],a:2,e:"Neck extension with proper head positioning aligns the oral cavity, pharynx, and esophageal inlet, facilitating safer rigid esophagoscopy.<br><br>Correct positioning minimizes mucosal trauma and reduces the risk of perforation at the cricopharyngeal narrowing during instrumentation.<br><br>Middle ear pressure (A) and salivary secretion (E) are unrelated to esophagoscopy positioning.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old smoker presents with progressive dysphagia initially to solids and later to liquids, associated with weight loss and unilateral referred otalgia. Flexible laryngoscopy shows pooling of saliva in the pyriform fossa. Which investigation is most important next?",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Barium swallow only","Direct hypopharyngoscopy and biopsy","Tympanometry","Vestibular testing"],a:2,e:"Progressive dysphagia with referred otalgia and pyriform sinus pooling strongly suggests hypopharyngeal or postcricoid malignancy. Direct endoscopic visualization allows definitive tissue diagnosis.<br><br>Biopsy is essential because imaging alone cannot reliably distinguish malignant from benign obstructive pathology. Early diagnosis significantly influences prognosis and treatment planning.<br><br>Audiometry (A), tympanometry (D), and vestibular testing (E) are unrelated investigations in suspected hypopharyngeal carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing rigid esophagoscopy for impacted foreign body suddenly develops neck swelling, fever, and crepitus postoperatively. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Esophageal perforation","Vocal nodule formation","Bell palsy","Acute sinusitis"],a:1,e:"Esophageal perforation is a feared complication of rigid esophagoscopy, particularly at the cricopharyngeal narrowing where instrumentation is technically difficult.<br><br>Air leakage into fascial planes produces surgical emphysema and crepitus, while contamination may rapidly progress to mediastinitis and sepsis. Prompt recognition is critical.<br><br>Vocal nodules (C) and sinusitis (E) do not explain postoperative cervical emphysema after esophagoscopy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing dysphagia develops recurrent aspiration pneumonia. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals unilateral vocal cord paralysis. Which mechanism most directly explains aspiration?",o:["Eustachian tube dysfunction","Increased salivary secretion","Incomplete glottic closure during swallowing","Nasal septal deviation","Cricothyroid spasm"],a:2,e:"The vocal cords protect the airway during deglutition by closing tightly during swallowing. Paralysis leaves a persistent glottic gap allowing aspiration of liquids and secretions.<br><br>Patients commonly present with coughing while eating, weak breathy voice, and recurrent lower respiratory infections. Flexible laryngoscopy confirms impaired cord mobility.<br><br>Nasal septal deviation (D) and eustachian dysfunction (A) are unrelated to aspiration mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Zenker diverticulum undergoes endoscopic stapling diverticulotomy. The procedure primarily works by dividing the:",o:["Thyrohyoid membrane","Superior constrictor muscle","Cricopharyngeus muscle","Epiglottic cartilage","Aryepiglottic fold"],a:2,e:"Zenker diverticulum develops due to dysfunctional cricopharyngeal relaxation producing increased pharyngeal pressure during swallowing. Endoscopic stapling divides the common wall and cricopharyngeus.<br><br>This reduces outflow obstruction and prevents further pouch filling, improving dysphagia and regurgitation symptoms significantly.<br><br>The superior constrictor (C) and aryepiglottic fold (E) are not the target structures in Zenker surgery.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and postcricoid growth develops severe anemia and weight loss. Which investigation best evaluates the full extent of disease spread?",o:["Audiometry","MRI internal auditory canal","Tympanometry","CT scan of neck and chest","Caloric testing"],a:3,e:"Cross-sectional imaging assesses local invasion, nodal metastasis, airway involvement, and mediastinal spread in postcricoid and upper esophageal malignancies.<br><br>Accurate staging is essential for planning surgery, radiotherapy, or combined oncologic treatment. Nutritional status and airway compromise must also be evaluated carefully.<br><br>Audiometry (A) and vestibular tests (E) are unrelated in upper digestive tract malignancy assessment.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with sudden drooling, dysphagia, and inability to swallow saliva after fish bone ingestion. Plain radiograph is inconclusive. What is the most appropriate next step?",o:["Observation only","Rigid esophagoscopy","Mastoid exploration","Tonsillectomy","Nasal packing"],a:1,e:"Persistent symptoms strongly suggest retained upper esophageal foreign body even when plain radiographs are negative, particularly with radiolucent fish bones.<br><br>Rigid esophagoscopy permits direct visualization and safe removal while minimizing risk of perforation and deep neck infection.<br><br>Observation alone (A) risks delayed complications including abscess formation and mediastinitis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe dysphagia and nasal regurgitation after skull base surgery. Which cranial nerve injury most likely contributed?",o:["Optic nerve","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Facial nerve only","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Oculomotor nerve"],a:3,e:"The glossopharyngeal nerve contributes significantly to pharyngeal sensation and swallowing coordination. Injury impairs initiation of swallowing and airway protection.<br><br>Patients commonly develop nasal regurgitation, aspiration, and absent gag reflex following lower cranial nerve dysfunction.<br><br>Optic (A) and oculomotor nerves (E) are unrelated to swallowing physiology.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia undergoes barium swallow showing posterior outpouching above the cricopharyngeus. The diagnosis is:",o:["Achalasia cardia","Zenker diverticulum","Esophageal varices","Barrett esophagus","Diffuse esophageal spasm"],a:1,e:"Zenker diverticulum appears radiologically as a posterior pharyngoesophageal pouch arising above the upper esophageal sphincter through Killian dehiscence.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of regurgitation, halitosis, nocturnal cough, and aspiration in addition to progressive dysphagia.<br><br>Achalasia (A) affects the distal esophagus and demonstrates a different radiological appearance.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During rigid esophagoscopy, the commonest site of foreign body impaction encountered by ENT surgeons is the:",o:["Gastroesophageal junction","Cricopharyngeal constriction","Mid-esophageal aortic constriction","Diaphragmatic hiatus","Pyloric sphincter"],a:1,e:"The cricopharyngeal narrowing is the narrowest segment of the adult esophagus and therefore the commonest site of foreign body impaction.<br><br>Coins, dentures, and fish bones frequently lodge here and may cause drooling, dysphagia, odynophagia, and airway compromise.<br><br>Lower constrictions (A, C, D) are less frequently encountered during ENT emergency foreign body management.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carcinoma postcricoid region develops hoarseness late in the disease course because of involvement of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Greater auricular nerve"],a:3,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve lies in the tracheoesophageal groove and may become compressed or infiltrated by advanced upper esophageal and hypopharyngeal tumors.<br><br>Hoarseness due to vocal cord paralysis usually suggests advanced local disease and poorer prognosis.<br><br>The facial nerve (A) and trigeminal nerve (D) do not course adjacent to the cervical esophagus.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops dysphagia and severe chest pain after forceful vomiting. Surgical emphysema is noted in the neck. Which diagnosis must be excluded urgently?",o:["Acute tonsillitis","Boerhaave syndrome","Vocal cord polyp","Ménière disease","Bell palsy"],a:1,e:"Boerhaave syndrome refers to spontaneous esophageal rupture caused by sudden rise in intraluminal pressure during forceful vomiting.<br><br>Air and contaminated contents track into cervical and mediastinal tissues, producing surgical emphysema, severe pain, sepsis, and mediastinitis. Immediate diagnosis is lifesaving.<br><br>Acute tonsillitis (A) does not produce mediastinal emphysema following vomiting.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe neurogenic dysphagia requires evaluation of aspiration risk during swallowing. Which investigation is most useful?",o:["Vestibular testing","CT temporal bone","Tympanometry","Videofluoroscopic swallow study","Pure tone audiometry"],a:3,e:"Videofluoroscopy dynamically evaluates oral, pharyngeal, and upper esophageal phases of swallowing while identifying aspiration and pooling abnormalities.<br><br>The study is particularly valuable in neurological dysphagia and postoperative swallowing rehabilitation planning.<br><br>Audiometry (E) and vestibular testing (A) do not assess swallowing physiology.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and iron deficiency anemia is diagnosed with Plummer-Vinson syndrome. Which malignancy risk is particularly increased?",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Postcricoid carcinoma","Thyroid lymphoma","Vestibular schwannoma","Parotid adenoma"],a:1,e:"Plummer-Vinson syndrome consists of iron deficiency anemia, upper esophageal webs, and dysphagia. It is associated with increased risk of postcricoid squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Patients therefore require careful long-term ENT surveillance even after correction of anemia and dysphagia.<br><br>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma (A) and thyroid lymphoma (C) are not characteristically associated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing rigid esophagoscopy suddenly develops oxygen desaturation and airway difficulty during the procedure. Which anatomical relationship is most relevant to this complication?",o:["Close relation between esophagus and larynx","Relation with middle ear cavity","Relation with parotid gland","Relation with maxillary sinus","Relation with cochlea"],a:0,e:"Rigid esophagoscopy requires manipulation close to the laryngeal inlet and upper airway. Edema, trauma, or aspiration may rapidly compromise ventilation during instrumentation.<br><br>Careful airway monitoring is therefore essential throughout esophageal procedures performed by ENT surgeons.<br><br>Middle ear (B) and cochlear relationships (E) are anatomically unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe cricopharyngeal achalasia undergoes cricopharyngeal myotomy. The primary goal of surgery is to:",o:["Remove the epiglottis","Increase salivary secretion","Widen the nasal cavity","Improve upper esophageal sphincter relaxation","Immobilize vocal cords"],a:3,e:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy relieves functional obstruction at the upper esophageal sphincter by dividing the cricopharyngeus muscle fibers.<br><br>Patients often experience marked improvement in swallowing and reduction in aspiration episodes after successful surgery.<br><br>The procedure does not directly affect nasal airflow (C) or vocal cord mobility (E).<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing dysphagia develops aspiration during sleep due to retained food within a pharyngoesophageal pouch. Which condition best explains this presentation?",o:["Zenker diverticulum","Achalasia cardia","Vocal cord granuloma","Acute epiglottitis","Peritonsillar abscess"],a:0,e:"Retained food within Zenker diverticulum may regurgitate during recumbency, producing nocturnal aspiration and recurrent chest infections.<br><br>Patients commonly describe halitosis, gurgling neck sounds, and regurgitation of undigested food hours after eating.<br><br>Achalasia (B) primarily affects distal esophageal motility rather than the pharyngoesophageal junction.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with upper esophageal malignancy develops tracheoesophageal fistula. Which symptom is most characteristic?",o:["Coughing immediately after swallowing","Conductive hearing loss","Persistent vertigo","Facial twitching","Tinnitus"],a:0,e:"Tracheoesophageal fistula allows swallowed material to enter the airway directly, producing coughing and recurrent aspiration during eating or drinking.<br><br>Severe chest infections and nutritional compromise frequently develop in advanced disease.<br><br>Hearing loss (B) and tinnitus (E) are unrelated to tracheoesophageal fistula formation.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with postoperative dysphagia after anterior cervical spine surgery most likely developed symptoms because the cervical esophagus is anatomically:",o:["Far from vertebral column","Surrounded by parotid tissue","Completely intrathoracic","Closely related to cervical vertebrae anteriorly","Located lateral to carotid sheath only"],a:3,e:"The cervical esophagus lies directly anterior to the cervical vertebral column and may be retracted or injured during anterior cervical spine procedures.<br><br>Transient postoperative dysphagia is therefore relatively common after cervical spinal surgery.<br><br>The esophagus is not intrathoracic throughout its course and is not surrounded by parotid tissue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia undergoes flexible endoscopic evaluation of swallowing (FEES). What is the major advantage of this investigation in ENT practice?",o:["Direct assessment of pharyngeal aspiration and residue","Evaluation of cochlear function","Measurement of vestibular reflexes","Visualization of middle ear ossicles","Assessment of sinus ventilation"],a:0,e:"FEES allows real-time visualization of pharyngeal residue, secretion pooling, penetration, and aspiration during swallowing using a flexible nasoendoscope.<br><br>It is highly valuable in neurogenic dysphagia, postoperative rehabilitation, and bedside swallowing assessment.<br><br>The procedure does not evaluate auditory or vestibular function.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe odynophagia and dysphagia after fish bone ingestion develops retropharyngeal abscess. Which mechanism most likely produced this complication?",o:["Middle ear infection spread","Eustachian tube dysfunction","Facial nerve compression","Penetration of mucosa with secondary deep neck infection","Cochlear inflammation"],a:3,e:"Sharp foreign bodies may penetrate the pharyngeal or esophageal wall, introducing infection into deep cervical spaces and producing abscess formation.<br><br>Patients may develop fever, neck swelling, trismus, dysphagia, and airway compromise requiring urgent drainage.<br><br>Middle ear disease (A) is unrelated to fish bone,associated deep neck infection.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 64-year-old patient with carcinoma postcricoid region undergoes total laryngopharyngectomy with gastric pull-up reconstruction. Which postoperative complication is most feared in the early period?",o:["Conductive hearing loss","Otosclerosis","Bell palsy","Pharyngocutaneous leak and mediastinitis","Nasal polyposis"],a:3,e:"Leakage from the pharyngogastric anastomosis may contaminate deep neck tissues and mediastinum, leading to severe sepsis and mediastinitis after major pharyngoesophageal reconstruction.<br><br>Patients commonly develop fever, neck swelling, salivary discharge, and systemic toxicity. Early recognition and aggressive management are essential for survival.<br><br>Otosclerosis (D) and nasal polyposis (E) are unrelated postoperative complications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe neurogenic dysphagia repeatedly aspirates despite swallowing rehabilitation. Which surgical procedure may be considered to protect the airway permanently?",o:["Septoplasty","Functional endoscopic sinus surgery","Laryngotracheal separation","Mastoidectomy","Tympanoplasty"],a:2,e:"Laryngotracheal separation prevents aspiration by permanently separating the airway from the pharynx while preserving the larynx anatomically. It is considered in severe intractable aspiration.<br><br>The procedure is particularly useful in advanced neurological disease when conservative swallowing rehabilitation has failed completely.<br><br>Septoplasty (A) and mastoidectomy (D) do not address aspiration-related dysphagia.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and upper esophageal carcinoma develops inspiratory stridor. Which mechanism most likely explains the airway compromise?",o:["Facial nerve compression","Conductive hearing loss","Direct laryngeal invasion or recurrent nerve involvement","Nasal obstruction","Vestibular dysfunction"],a:2,e:"Advanced upper esophageal tumors may invade the larynx or impair recurrent laryngeal nerve function, producing vocal cord paralysis and airway narrowing.<br><br>Stridor in this setting indicates advanced disease and may necessitate urgent tracheostomy to secure the airway before definitive oncologic treatment.<br><br>Vestibular dysfunction (E) and facial nerve compression (C) are unrelated to airway compromise in esophageal malignancy.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During rigid esophagoscopy for impacted denture removal, resistance is encountered at the cricopharyngeal narrowing. Excessive force at this point risks injury mainly to the:",o:["Posterior esophageal wall","Cricoarytenoid joint","Tympanic membrane","Facial nerve trunk","Maxillary sinus"],a:0,e:"The posterior wall at the cricopharyngeal region is particularly vulnerable during rigid esophagoscopy because it is relatively unsupported and anatomically narrow.<br><br>Perforation may rapidly lead to cervical emphysema, mediastinitis, sepsis, and significant mortality if diagnosis is delayed.<br><br>Cricoarytenoid joints (B) may be traumatized during intubation but are not the usual perforation site in esophagoscopy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing dysphagia and severe reflux develops chronic hoarseness, throat clearing, and posterior laryngeal edema on laryngoscopy. Which diagnosis best explains the ENT findings?",o:["Ménière disease","Laryngopharyngeal reflux","Bell palsy","Otosclerosis","Acute mastoiditis"],a:1,e:"Laryngopharyngeal reflux occurs when gastric acid and pepsin reach the laryngeal mucosa, causing chronic inflammation and edema of posterior laryngeal structures.<br><br>Patients commonly present to ENT clinics with hoarseness, globus sensation, throat clearing, and chronic cough rather than typical heartburn alone.<br><br>Ménière disease (A) and mastoiditis (E) do not produce posterior laryngitis associated with reflux dysphagia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 3-year-old child presents with sudden drooling, dysphagia, and refusal to eat after playing with coins. The commonest site of esophageal foreign body impaction is the:",o:["Gastroesophageal junction","Cricopharyngeal narrowing","Aortic constriction","Diaphragmatic hiatus","Lower esophageal sphincter"],a:1,e:"The cricopharyngeal constriction is the narrowest part of the esophagus and therefore the commonest site of foreign body impaction in ENT practice.<br><br>Children frequently present with drooling, dysphagia, neck discomfort, and inability to swallow saliva after accidental ingestion of coins or similar objects.<br><br>Lower esophageal constrictions (A, C, D) are less frequent impaction sites in pediatric emergencies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with suspected esophageal coin ingestion undergoes radiography. Which radiographic finding most strongly supports esophageal rather than tracheal location?",o:["Coin seen edge-on in AP view","Hyperinflated lungs","Coin located below diaphragm","Coin seen en face in AP view","Air-fluid level in sinus"],a:3,e:"Coins lodged in the esophagus typically align coronally and therefore appear en face on AP radiographs. Tracheal coins usually orient sagittally and appear edge-on.<br><br>Correct identification is essential because airway foreign bodies require more urgent airway intervention than esophageal impactions.<br><br>Pulmonary hyperinflation (D) suggests bronchial obstruction rather than esophageal foreign body impaction.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe chest pain, fever, and cervical emphysema after rigid esophagoscopy for fish bone removal. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Acute otitis media","Esophageal perforation","Bell palsy","Vocal nodule formation","Acute sinusitis"],a:1,e:"Esophageal perforation is a serious complication of rigid esophagoscopy, especially during removal of sharp foreign bodies such as fish bones.<br><br>Air leakage into fascial planes causes cervical emphysema, while contamination may rapidly progress to mediastinitis and sepsis. Prompt recognition is essential.<br><br>Bell palsy (C) and otitis media (A) do not explain postoperative surgical emphysema.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted denture in the upper esophagus is at particularly high risk of perforation because dentures:",o:["Are radiolucent only","Migrate into nasal cavity","Dissolve rapidly in saliva","Possess sharp metallic components","Produce facial paralysis"],a:3,e:"Dentures frequently contain sharp hooks or metallic clasps capable of penetrating esophageal mucosa during impaction or extraction attempts.<br><br>Perforation risk increases significantly during removal, particularly at the cricopharyngeal narrowing where maneuvering space is limited.<br><br>Radiolucency (A) complicates diagnosis but is not itself the reason for increased perforation risk.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with drooling and dysphagia after battery ingestion. Which factor makes button batteries especially dangerous in the esophagus?",o:["Mechanical obstruction only","Rapid alkali tissue necrosis","Increased salivation alone","Induction of vertigo","Facial nerve injury"],a:1,e:"Button batteries generate hydroxide ions at the negative pole, causing rapid liquefaction necrosis and deep tissue injury within hours.<br><br>Complications include perforation, tracheoesophageal fistula, mediastinitis, and catastrophic vascular erosion. Immediate endoscopic removal is mandatory.<br><br>Mechanical obstruction (A) alone does not explain the severe tissue destruction associated with battery ingestion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 5-year-old child presents with persistent drooling and inability to swallow after coin ingestion. Which procedure is the preferred treatment?",o:["Observation for one week","Mastoid exploration","Nasal packing","Rigid esophagoscopy under general anesthesia","Tympanoplasty"],a:3,e:"Rigid esophagoscopy remains the standard ENT procedure for removal of impacted upper esophageal foreign bodies in children.<br><br>General anesthesia provides airway protection and allows controlled extraction while minimizing risk of perforation and aspiration.<br><br>Delayed observation (A) risks pressure necrosis and worsening obstruction.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fish bone impaction complains of severe odynophagia despite normal plain radiographs. What is the most appropriate next step?",o:["Reassurance only","Vestibular testing","Hearing assessment","Endoscopic evaluation","Thyroidectomy"],a:3,e:"Fish bones are frequently radiolucent and may not appear on plain radiographs despite persistent impaction. Severe odynophagia strongly suggests retained foreign body.<br><br>Endoscopic examination allows direct visualization and removal while preventing delayed perforation and deep neck infection.<br><br>Hearing assessment (C) and vestibular testing (D) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal foreign body develops coughing immediately after swallowing liquids. Which complication should be suspected?",o:["Vocal cord granuloma","Ménière disease","Acute mastoiditis","Tracheoesophageal fistula","Bell palsy"],a:3,e:"Sharp or prolonged foreign body impaction may erode through the esophageal wall into the trachea, forming a tracheoesophageal fistula.<br><br>Patients develop coughing during swallowing, recurrent aspiration, and chest infections because liquids enter the airway directly.<br><br>Ménière disease (D) and Bell palsy (E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During rigid esophagoscopy, neck extension is used primarily to:",o:["Reduce middle ear pressure","Immobilize vocal cords","Increase salivation","Align oral cavity, pharynx, and esophagus","Improve cochlear perfusion"],a:3,e:"Proper neck extension aligns the upper digestive tract, facilitating safer passage of the rigid esophagoscope through the cricopharyngeal region.<br><br>Correct positioning minimizes mucosal trauma and decreases risk of perforation during instrumentation.<br><br>Middle ear pressure (A) and cochlear perfusion (E) are unrelated to esophagoscopy positioning.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops mediastinitis following delayed diagnosis of esophageal perforation. The infection spreads rapidly because cervical fascial planes:",o:["Are completely sealed compartments","Are lined by cartilage","Contain no lymphatics","Communicate directly with mediastinum","Prevent downward spread of infection"],a:3,e:"Deep cervical fascial spaces communicate freely with the mediastinum, allowing rapid spread of air, saliva, and infection after esophageal perforation.<br><br>Mediastinitis is therefore a life-threatening emergency associated with significant morbidity and mortality if treatment is delayed.<br><br>The fascial planes do not prevent infection spread and are not sealed compartments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with prolonged impacted foreign body develops fever, neck swelling, and trismus. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Otosclerosis","Acute glaucoma","Bell palsy","Tympanic membrane perforation"],a:0,e:"Sharp foreign bodies may penetrate the posterior pharyngeal or esophageal wall, introducing infection into deep neck spaces and producing retropharyngeal abscess.<br><br>Patients commonly develop fever, neck stiffness, dysphagia, muffled voice, and airway compromise requiring urgent drainage.<br><br>Bell palsy (D) and otosclerosis (B) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted esophageal foreign body develops hoarseness due to involvement of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve only"],a:3,e:"Inflammation or direct compression near the tracheoesophageal groove may affect the recurrent laryngeal nerve, producing unilateral vocal cord paralysis and hoarseness.<br><br>Persistent hoarseness after foreign body impaction should raise suspicion of local tissue injury or advanced complications.<br><br>The facial nerve (A) and vestibulocochlear nerve (C) are anatomically unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with esophageal button battery ingestion should undergo removal:",o:["Within several weeks","After trial of antibiotics","Only if symptoms appear","Immediately as an emergency","After audiometry"],a:3,e:"Button batteries can cause severe caustic injury within hours because of electrical discharge and alkali generation. Delay markedly increases risk of perforation and fistula formation.<br><br>Immediate endoscopic removal is therefore mandatory even if symptoms initially appear mild.<br><br>Observation alone (C) is dangerous and inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted upper esophageal denture undergoes difficult rigid esophagoscopy. Which structure is most vulnerable to perforation?",o:["Posterior esophageal wall","Nasal septum","Middle turbinate","Tympanic membrane","Facial artery"],a:0,e:"The posterior wall at the cricopharyngeal region is thin and relatively unsupported, making it particularly vulnerable during difficult instrumentation.<br><br>Perforation may rapidly progress to cervical emphysema and mediastinitis, especially with delayed diagnosis.<br><br>The tympanic membrane (D) and nasal septum (B) are unrelated structures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with persistent foreign body sensation after fish bone ingestion despite normal examination. Which investigation is most useful when suspicion remains high?",o:["MRI brain","Flexible endoscopy","Pure tone audiometry","Vestibular assessment","Tympanometry"],a:1,e:"Flexible endoscopy permits direct visualization of the pharynx and upper esophagus and is highly valuable when radiographs are negative but symptoms persist.<br><br>Early identification prevents delayed complications such as perforation, abscess formation, and chronic inflammation.<br><br>Audiometry (C) and vestibular assessment (D) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal perforation after foreign body removal most commonly develops pain in the:",o:["Forehead only","Orbit","Ear canal only","Neck and chest","Mastoid region"],a:3,e:"Perforation causes leakage of saliva and air into cervical and mediastinal tissues, producing severe neck and retrosternal pain.<br><br>Fever, tachycardia, crepitus, and dysphagia commonly accompany the condition and require urgent intervention.<br><br>Orbital pain (D) and mastoid pain (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which foreign body is most likely to pass spontaneously through the esophagus in children?",o:["Sharp denture","Button battery","Small smooth coin","Open safety pin","Fish hook"],a:2,e:"Small smooth blunt objects located distally may pass spontaneously through the gastrointestinal tract without intervention.<br><br>However, persistent symptoms, upper esophageal impaction, or airway compromise still require urgent endoscopic removal.<br><br>Button batteries (B) and sharp objects (A, D, E) demand prompt extraction because of high complication risk.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing impacted foreign body develops massive hematemesis. Which catastrophic complication should be suspected?",o:["Vocal cord granuloma","Acute sinusitis","Bell palsy","Aortoesophageal fistula","Ménière disease"],a:3,e:"Sharp foreign bodies or prolonged impaction may erode into adjacent major vessels such as the aorta, causing catastrophic hemorrhage.<br><br>Sentinel bleeding may precede fatal hematemesis, making this one of the most feared complications of esophageal foreign bodies.<br><br>Granulomas (A) and sinusitis (D) do not cause massive upper gastrointestinal bleeding.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing rigid esophagoscopy suddenly develops oxygen desaturation during extraction of a large foreign body. Which factor is most responsible?",o:["Temporary airway compromise by instrumentation","Cochlear ischemia","Tympanic membrane rupture","Eustachian tube edema","Facial nerve compression"],a:0,e:"Large esophagoscopes and impacted foreign bodies may transiently compress or obstruct the laryngeal inlet during extraction. Continuous airway monitoring is therefore essential.<br><br>Children are especially vulnerable because of smaller airway caliber and rapid oxygen desaturation under anesthesia.<br><br>Cochlear ischemia (B) and tympanic membrane rupture (C) are unrelated intraoperative concerns.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted fish bone develops persistent neck swelling and fever several days later. CT scan shows deep neck collection. Which complication has most likely occurred?",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Facial nerve palsy","Acute otitis media","Deep neck abscess secondary to perforation","Cholesteatoma"],a:3,e:"Sharp fish bones may perforate the pharyngeal or esophageal wall, introducing infection into cervical fascial spaces.<br><br>Delayed presentation with fever, neck swelling, trismus, and dysphagia strongly suggests deep neck space infection requiring drainage and antibiotics.<br><br>Otitis media (C) and cholesteatoma (E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted upper esophageal foreign body complains mainly of pain localized to the neck rather than chest because the lesion is:",o:["Cervical in location","Intracranial in origin","Pulmonary in nature","Otologic in origin","Gastric in location"],a:0,e:"Upper esophageal foreign bodies near the cricopharyngeus commonly produce localized cervical pain and dysphagia because of proximity to neck structures.<br><br>Lower thoracic impactions more often produce retrosternal discomfort and chest pain.<br><br>Intracranial (B) and pulmonary (C) pathology are unrelated to localized cervical odynophagia after swallowing.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with upper esophageal coin impaction develops stridor. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Middle ear infection","Facial nerve compression","Cochlear dysfunction","Compression of posterior tracheal wall","Tympanic membrane edema"],a:3,e:"Large foreign bodies lodged at the upper esophagus may compress the relatively soft posterior tracheal wall in children, producing airway compromise and stridor.<br><br>Airway symptoms require urgent removal because progressive obstruction may occur rapidly in pediatric patients.<br><br>Middle ear infection (A) and cochlear dysfunction (C) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most useful for evaluating suspected perforation after foreign body removal?",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Vestibular testing","Tympanometry","Contrast-enhanced CT neck and chest","Nasal endoscopy only"],a:3,e:"CT imaging accurately identifies extraluminal air, fluid collections, mediastinal involvement, and abscess formation following suspected esophageal perforation.<br><br>Early diagnosis guides urgent surgical or conservative management and improves outcomes significantly.<br><br>Audiometry (A) and vestibular testing (D) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted foreign body develops recurrent aspiration pneumonia weeks later. Which delayed complication should be suspected?",o:["Tracheoesophageal fistula","Bell palsy","Ménière disease","Acute mastoiditis","Otosclerosis"],a:0,e:"Chronic erosion between esophagus and trachea may occur after prolonged foreign body impaction, especially with sharp objects or batteries.<br><br>Patients commonly develop coughing during swallowing and recurrent aspiration-related chest infections.<br><br>Ménière disease (C) and otosclerosis (E) are unrelated ENT disorders.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with impacted esophageal foreign body develops sudden severe hematemesis during attempted removal. Immediate concern should be:",o:["Vocal cord edema only","Tympanic membrane perforation","Acute sinusitis","Major vascular erosion","Bell palsy"],a:3,e:"Sharp or long-standing foreign bodies may erode into adjacent great vessels such as the aorta or subclavian artery, producing catastrophic hemorrhage.<br><br>Massive hematemesis during manipulation is a surgical emergency requiring immediate airway stabilization and vascular control.<br><br>Sinusitis (C) and tympanic membrane perforation (D) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old smoker presents with progressive dysphagia initially to solids and later to liquids, associated with weight loss and hoarseness. Which diagnosis should be suspected first in ENT practice?",o:["Achalasia cardia","Upper esophageal carcinoma","Globus pharyngeus","Acute tonsillitis","Cricopharyngeal spasm"],a:1,e:"Progressive dysphagia with weight loss and hoarseness is highly suspicious for malignancy involving the upper esophagus or hypopharynx. Recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement may produce vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>ENT evaluation should include flexible laryngoscopy, imaging, and endoscopic biopsy for definitive diagnosis and staging.<br><br>Globus sensation (C) usually occurs without progressive obstruction or constitutional symptoms.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Zenker diverticulum most commonly complains of:",o:["Conductive hearing loss","Vertigo","Facial weakness","Regurgitation of undigested food","Epistaxis"],a:3,e:"Zenker diverticulum causes retention of food within a pharyngoesophageal pouch, leading to regurgitation hours after eating. Halitosis and aspiration are additional classic symptoms.<br><br>Nocturnal coughing and recurrent aspiration pneumonia commonly occur in advanced disease because retained food spills into the airway.<br><br>Vertigo (D) and epistaxis (E) are unrelated clinical features.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The weakest area responsible for development of Zenker diverticulum is:",o:["Rosenmüller fossa","Killian dehiscence","Broyles ligament","Cricothyroid membrane","Pyriform recess"],a:1,e:"Killian dehiscence is a weak area between thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus muscle fibers. Increased intraluminal pressure may force mucosa through this region.<br><br>The resulting pulsion diverticulum produces dysphagia, aspiration, and regurgitation of retained food.<br><br>Broyles ligament (C) is related to the anterior commissure of the larynx rather than the esophagus.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Plummer-Vinson syndrome is particularly at increased risk of developing:",o:["Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Postcricoid carcinoma","Vestibular schwannoma","Cholesteatoma","Bell palsy"],a:1,e:"Plummer-Vinson syndrome consists of iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia, and upper esophageal webs. It carries increased malignant potential for postcricoid squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Patients require long-term ENT surveillance even after correction of anemia and swallowing symptoms.<br><br>Vestibular schwannoma (C) and cholesteatoma (D) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with achalasia cardia most commonly demonstrates failure of relaxation of the:",o:["Upper esophageal sphincter","Pyriform sinus","Cricopharyngeus only","Lower esophageal sphincter","Vocal cords"],a:3,e:"Achalasia results from impaired relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter combined with abnormal esophageal peristalsis. Dysphagia affects both solids and liquids early.<br><br>Patients may additionally complain of regurgitation, chest pain, aspiration, and weight loss.<br><br>The upper esophageal sphincter (A) is typically unaffected in classic achalasia.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal perforation develops severe chest pain, fever, and cervical emphysema. Which complication is most feared?",o:["Otosclerosis","Acute glaucoma","Bell palsy","Mediastinitis","Tympanic membrane rupture"],a:3,e:"Esophageal perforation allows contamination of mediastinal tissues by saliva and bacteria, producing rapidly progressive mediastinitis and sepsis.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis significantly increases mortality, making early recognition and urgent management essential.<br><br>Otosclerosis (A) and Bell palsy (C) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe reflux disease develops chronic hoarseness, throat clearing, and posterior laryngeal edema. Which diagnosis best explains the ENT manifestations?",o:["Ménière disease","Otosclerosis","Acute mastoiditis","Laryngopharyngeal reflux","Bell palsy"],a:3,e:"Laryngopharyngeal reflux occurs when gastric contents reach the laryngeal mucosa, causing chronic inflammation and edema of posterior laryngeal structures.<br><br>Patients commonly present to ENT clinics with hoarseness, globus sensation, chronic cough, and throat clearing.<br><br>Mastoiditis (C) and Bell palsy (E) do not produce posterior laryngitis associated with reflux.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and unilateral vocal cord paralysis most likely has involvement of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:3,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove and may be compressed or infiltrated by upper esophageal malignancies.<br><br>Hoarseness in association with dysphagia usually indicates advanced disease requiring urgent evaluation.<br><br>The facial nerve (A) and vestibulocochlear nerve (C) are anatomically unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neurogenic dysphagia undergoes videofluoroscopic swallow study. The primary purpose of this investigation is to assess:",o:["Middle ear ventilation","Cochlear function","Vestibular reflexes","Aspiration and swallowing dynamics","Sinus drainage"],a:3,e:"Videofluoroscopy dynamically evaluates oral, pharyngeal, and upper esophageal phases of swallowing while identifying aspiration risk and pooling abnormalities.<br><br>It is especially useful in neurological disease and postoperative swallowing rehabilitation planning.<br><br>Middle ear ventilation (A) and vestibular reflexes (C) are unrelated assessments.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing corrosive ingestion develops progressive dysphagia months later. The most likely pathology is:",o:["Vocal cord paralysis","Esophageal stricture formation","Acute mastoiditis","Bell palsy","Otitis externa"],a:1,e:"Corrosive injuries heal by fibrosis and scarring, producing progressive esophageal narrowing and dysphagia weeks to months after ingestion.<br><br>Repeated dilatation or reconstructive surgery may be required in severe strictures. Nutritional compromise is common.<br><br>Otitis externa (E) and mastoiditis (C) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and halitosis is found to have Zenker diverticulum. Which investigation classically demonstrates the lesion?",o:["Tympanometry","CT temporal bone","Audiometry","Barium swallow study","Vestibular testing"],a:3,e:"Barium swallow demonstrates the characteristic posterior pharyngoesophageal pouch arising above the cricopharyngeus.<br><br>The investigation also evaluates size of the pouch and degree of retention before operative planning.<br><br>Audiometry (C) and vestibular testing (E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after stroke is at greatest risk of:",o:["Otosclerosis","Ménière disease","Cholesteatoma","Bell palsy","Aspiration pneumonia"],a:4,e:"Neurological impairment disrupts airway protection during swallowing, allowing aspiration of food and secretions into the lower respiratory tract.<br><br>Aspiration pneumonia remains a major cause of morbidity and mortality in severe neurogenic dysphagia.<br><br>Ménière disease (E) and cholesteatoma (C) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with postcricoid carcinoma most commonly presents initially with:",o:["Facial numbness","Progressive dysphagia","Conductive deafness","Severe vertigo","Diplopia"],a:1,e:"Postcricoid tumors gradually narrow the upper digestive tract lumen, causing progressive dysphagia particularly for solids.<br><br>Weight loss, aspiration, and cervical nodal metastases often develop later in disease progression.<br><br>Vertigo (D) and diplopia (E) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy is performed primarily to treat:",o:["Vocal nodules","Otosclerosis","Bell palsy","Nasal obstruction","Cricopharyngeal dysfunction"],a:4,e:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy divides the dysfunctional upper esophageal sphincter muscle to improve swallowing and reduce aspiration.<br><br>The procedure is commonly used in selected cases of Zenker diverticulum and neurogenic dysphagia.<br><br>Vocal nodules (A) and nasal obstruction (D) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with upper esophageal carcinoma develops coughing immediately after swallowing liquids. Which complication should be suspected?",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Ménière disease","Bell palsy","Otitis externa","Tracheoesophageal fistula"],a:4,e:"Tumor erosion between the esophagus and trachea allows swallowed contents to enter the airway directly, producing coughing during meals.<br><br>Aspiration pneumonia and severe nutritional compromise commonly follow advanced fistula formation.<br><br>Otitis externa (D) and Bell palsy (C) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sudden severe chest pain after forceful vomiting develops cervical emphysema. Which diagnosis must be excluded urgently?",o:["Acute sinusitis","Boerhaave syndrome","Cholesteatoma","Bell palsy","Ménière disease"],a:1,e:"Boerhaave syndrome is spontaneous transmural esophageal rupture caused by sudden increase in intraluminal pressure during forceful vomiting.<br><br>Cervical emphysema, severe chest pain, and sepsis are classic findings requiring urgent diagnosis and management.<br><br>Sinusitis (A) and Ménière disease (E) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and iron deficiency anemia undergoes endoscopy showing upper esophageal webs. The diagnosis is:",o:["Barrett esophagus","Esophageal varices","Achalasia","Diffuse esophageal spasm","Plummer-Vinson syndrome"],a:4,e:"Plummer-Vinson syndrome combines iron deficiency anemia, upper esophageal webs, and dysphagia. It is particularly important in ENT oncology because of malignant potential.<br><br>Patients require surveillance for postcricoid carcinoma even after symptomatic improvement.<br><br>Achalasia (C) affects the lower esophageal sphincter rather than producing cervical webs.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of Zenker diverticulum is:",o:["Hearing loss","Epistaxis","Facial paralysis","Vertigo","Dysphagia"],a:4,e:"Progressive oropharyngeal dysphagia is the commonest presenting complaint in Zenker diverticulum because retained food obstructs normal swallowing.<br><br>Regurgitation, aspiration, and halitosis often accompany advanced disease.<br><br>Vertigo (D) and facial paralysis (C) are unrelated manifestations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe reflux develops chronic posterior laryngitis. Which laryngeal finding is commonly associated with reflux disease?",o:["Facial nerve palsy","Tympanic membrane perforation","Posterior commissure hypertrophy","Cholesteatoma","Nasal septal perforation"],a:2,e:"Chronic acid exposure causes edema and hypertrophy of posterior laryngeal structures including the posterior commissure and arytenoids.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of throat clearing, chronic cough, and persistent hoarseness.<br><br>Cholesteatoma (D) and tympanic membrane perforation (B) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia undergoes upper GI endoscopy. The main advantage of endoscopy over barium swallow is:",o:["Assessment of hearing","Visualization of mastoid air cells","Measurement of vestibular reflexes","Evaluation of cochlear function","Ability to obtain biopsy"],a:4,e:"Endoscopy permits direct visualization of lesions and acquisition of tissue samples for histopathological diagnosis, which is essential in suspected malignancy.<br><br>Barium studies may demonstrate structural narrowing but cannot provide definitive tissue diagnosis.<br><br>Vestibular testing (C) and cochlear evaluation (D) are unrelated functions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after radiotherapy for hypopharyngeal carcinoma most likely developed:",o:["Fibrotic stricture formation","Acute otitis media","Bell palsy","Cholesteatoma","Ménière disease"],a:0,e:"Radiotherapy may produce progressive fibrosis and narrowing of the pharyngoesophageal segment, leading to delayed dysphagia and aspiration.<br><br>Endoscopic dilatation or reconstructive surgery may be necessary in severe strictures.<br><br>Otitis media (B) and cholesteatoma (D) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia develops aspiration mainly because of failure of:",o:["Glottic closure during swallowing","Middle ear ventilation","Cochlear amplification","Facial expression","Nasal mucociliary clearance"],a:0,e:"Normal swallowing requires coordinated laryngeal elevation and vocal cord adduction to protect the airway. Failure predisposes to aspiration.<br><br>Patients commonly present with coughing during meals and recurrent chest infections.<br><br>Cochlear amplification (C) and nasal clearance (E) are unrelated physiological processes.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with achalasia cardia typically experiences dysphagia to:",o:["Solids only initially","Both solids and liquids from onset","Liquids only","Cold foods only","Spicy foods only"],a:1,e:"Achalasia is primarily a motility disorder rather than a structural obstruction, so dysphagia affects both solids and liquids early in the disease course.<br><br>Regurgitation, aspiration, and chest discomfort are additional common symptoms.<br><br>Mechanical obstruction usually progresses from solids to liquids rather than affecting both simultaneously initially.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal disorder develops hoarseness because of recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement. The nerve is anatomically related to the:",o:["Maxillary sinus","Orbit","External auditory canal","Mastoid antrum","Tracheoesophageal groove"],a:4,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove before entering the larynx, making it vulnerable to esophageal pathology.<br><br>Compression or invasion by tumors commonly produces unilateral vocal cord paralysis and hoarseness.<br><br>The orbit (E) and mastoid antrum (D) are unrelated structures.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia and aspiration secondary to Zenker diverticulum undergoes endoscopic stapling diverticulotomy. The operation works mainly by:",o:["Removing the thyroid gland","Excising vocal cords","Widening the nasal cavity","Immobilizing the epiglottis","Dividing the cricopharyngeus muscle"],a:4,e:"Endoscopic stapling creates a common channel between the esophagus and diverticular pouch while simultaneously dividing the dysfunctional cricopharyngeus muscle.<br><br>This relieves outflow obstruction and reduces food retention, regurgitation, and aspiration symptoms.<br><br>The procedure does not involve thyroidectomy (A) or vocal cord excision (E).<br><br>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia, iron deficiency anemia, and upper esophageal web most likely has:",o:["Achalasia cardia","Boerhaave syndrome","Diffuse esophageal spasm","Barrett esophagus","Plummer-Vinson syndrome"],a:4,e:"Plummer-Vinson syndrome classically consists of the triad of dysphagia, iron deficiency anemia, and upper esophageal webs. It is strongly associated with postcricoid carcinoma risk.<br><br>Patients commonly present in ENT clinics with slowly progressive dysphagia, glossitis, koilonychia, and fatigue. Endoscopic evaluation and surveillance remain important because of malignant potential.<br><br>Achalasia (A) affects the lower esophageal sphincter rather than causing cervical webs.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of esophageal foreign body impaction in ENT practice is:",o:["Lower esophageal sphincter","Cricopharyngeal constriction","Diaphragmatic hiatus","Mid-thoracic esophagus","Gastroesophageal junction"],a:1,e:"The cricopharyngeal narrowing is the narrowest part of the esophagus and therefore the most common site of foreign body impaction.<br><br>Coins, dentures, and fish bones frequently lodge at this level, producing dysphagia, drooling, odynophagia, and sometimes airway compromise.<br><br>Lower esophageal constrictions (A, C, E) are less commonly involved in ENT emergency practice.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Zenker diverticulum most commonly presents with:",o:["Regurgitation of undigested food","Severe epistaxis","Conductive hearing loss","Facial weakness","Diplopia"],a:0,e:"Zenker diverticulum causes retention of food within a pharyngoesophageal pouch, resulting in regurgitation hours after eating. Aspiration and halitosis are additional classic features. Nocturnal coughing and recurrent aspiration pneumonia commonly occur in advanced disease because retained food spills into the airway during recumbency.<br><br>Diplopia (E) and facial weakness (D) are unrelated manifestations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Killian dehiscence is located between fibers of the:",o:["Superior and middle constrictors","Sternohyoid and thyrohyoid","Stylopharyngeus and salpingopharyngeus","Cricothyroid and thyroarytenoid","Thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus"],a:4,e:"Killian dehiscence is a weak triangular area between oblique thyropharyngeus fibers and transverse cricopharyngeus fibers. Zenker diverticulum develops through this region. Failure of proper cricopharyngeal relaxation increases intrapharyngeal pressure and contributes to pouch formation.<br><br>The remaining muscular relationships are anatomically unrelated to pharyngoesophageal diverticula.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and unilateral vocal cord paralysis most likely has involvement of the:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Trigeminal nerve"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove and may be infiltrated by upper esophageal or postcricoid malignancies.<br><br>Hoarseness associated with dysphagia is therefore an important red flag for advanced malignant disease in ENT practice.<br><br>Facial (A) and trigeminal nerves (E) are unrelated anatomically.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with achalasia cardia typically develops dysphagia to:",o:["Solids only initially","Liquids only","Both solids and liquids from onset","Hot foods only","Cold foods only"],a:2,e:"Achalasia is primarily a motility disorder rather than a mechanical obstruction. Dysphagia therefore affects both solids and liquids early in the disease course.<br><br>Regurgitation, aspiration, and retrosternal discomfort are common associated features.<br><br>Mechanical obstruction usually progresses from solids to liquids rather than involving both initially.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe chest pain and cervical emphysema after forceful vomiting. Which diagnosis should be excluded urgently?",o:["Mallory-Weiss tear","Ménière disease","Acute tonsillitis","Bell palsy","Boerhaave syndrome"],a:4,e:"Boerhaave syndrome refers to spontaneous transmural esophageal rupture caused by sudden increase in intraluminal pressure during vomiting.<br><br>Air leakage produces cervical emphysema, mediastinitis, and rapidly progressive sepsis requiring urgent diagnosis and treatment.<br><br>Mallory-Weiss tears (A) are usually mucosal and less catastrophic.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The gold standard investigation for Zenker diverticulum is:",o:["Audiometry","CT temporal bone","Tympanometry","MRI brain","Barium swallow"],a:4,e:"Barium swallow demonstrates the characteristic posterior pharyngoesophageal pouch arising above the cricopharyngeus. The study also helps determine pouch size and guides operative planning before endoscopic or open repair.<br><br>Audiometry (A) and tympanometry (C) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe neurogenic dysphagia is at greatest risk of:",o:["Otosclerosis","Bell palsy","Aspiration pneumonia","Cholesteatoma","Ménière disease"],a:2,e:"Neurological dysphagia impairs airway protection during swallowing, allowing food and secretions to enter the respiratory tract.<br><br>Aspiration pneumonia is therefore a major source of morbidity and mortality in patients with severe swallowing dysfunction.<br><br>Ménière disease (E) and cholesteatoma (D) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy is primarily performed to treat:",o:["Otosclerosis","Nasal obstruction","Cricopharyngeal dysfunction","Vocal nodules","Bell palsy"],a:2,e:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy divides the dysfunctional upper esophageal sphincter muscle to improve bolus passage and reduce aspiration.<br><br>It is commonly used in selected cases of Zenker diverticulum and neurogenic dysphagia.<br><br>Vocal nodules (D) and nasal obstruction (B) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic reflux develops hoarseness and posterior laryngeal edema. Which ENT diagnosis best explains these findings?",o:["Acute mastoiditis","Otitis externa","Ménière disease","Bell palsy","Laryngopharyngeal reflux"],a:4,e:"Laryngopharyngeal reflux occurs when gastric acid and pepsin reach the laryngeal mucosa, causing chronic inflammation and edema.<br><br>Patients frequently present with throat clearing, globus sensation, chronic cough, and dysphonia.<br><br>Mastoiditis (A) and Bell palsy (D) do not produce posterior laryngitis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and halitosis most likely has:",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Nasal polyp","Otitis externa","Bell palsy","Zenker diverticulum"],a:4,e:"Food retention within the diverticular pouch leads to bacterial decomposition and characteristic foul breath odor in Zenker diverticulum.<br><br>Regurgitation, aspiration, and gurgling neck sensation are additional high-yield features.<br><br>Acute epiglottitis (A) presents primarily with fever and airway compromise rather than halitosis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with postcricoid carcinoma most commonly presents initially with:",o:["Progressive dysphagia","Hearing loss","Facial paralysis","Vertigo","Epistaxis"],a:0,e:"Postcricoid tumors gradually narrow the upper digestive tract lumen, producing progressive dysphagia particularly for solids initially.<br><br>Weight loss, aspiration, and cervical nodal metastases often appear later during disease progression.<br><br>Vertigo (D) and hearing loss (B) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after corrosive ingestion most likely developed:",o:["Vocal cord polyp","Acute mastoiditis","Otosclerosis","Bell palsy","Esophageal stricture"],a:4,e:"Corrosive injuries heal by fibrosis and scarring, leading to progressive esophageal narrowing and severe dysphagia weeks to months later.<br><br>Repeated dilatation or reconstructive surgery may become necessary in severe cases.<br><br>Bell palsy (D) and mastoiditis (E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with upper esophageal carcinoma develops coughing immediately after swallowing liquids. Which complication should be suspected?",o:["Tracheoesophageal fistula","Ménière disease","Bell palsy","Acute sinusitis","Otitis externa"],a:0,e:"Tumor erosion between the trachea and esophagus allows swallowed contents to enter the airway directly, producing coughing during swallowing.<br><br>Aspiration pneumonia and nutritional compromise are common consequences of advanced fistula formation.<br><br>Ménière disease (B) and Bell palsy (C) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of esophageal web is:",o:["Dysphagia to solids","Severe vertigo","Facial numbness","Conductive hearing loss","Diplopia"],a:0,e:"Esophageal webs partially obstruct the upper esophageal lumen and therefore initially impair swallowing of solid foods.<br><br>Patients with Plummer-Vinson syndrome commonly present with painless slowly progressive dysphagia and iron deficiency anemia.<br><br>Vertigo (B) and hearing loss (D) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Zenker diverticulum undergoes endoscopic stapling diverticulotomy. The operation mainly works by dividing the:",o:["Epiglottis","Thyroid cartilage","Cricopharyngeus muscle","Vocal cords","Arytenoid cartilage"],a:2,e:"Endoscopic stapling creates a common channel between the esophagus and diverticular pouch while simultaneously dividing the dysfunctional cricopharyngeus. This relieves outflow obstruction and improves dysphagia, regurgitation, and aspiration symptoms.<br><br>The operation does not involve division of thyroid cartilage (B) or vocal cords (D).<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after stroke should ideally undergo:",o:["Tympanometry","CT temporal bone","Audiometry","Vestibular testing","Videofluoroscopic swallow study"],a:4,e:"Videofluoroscopy dynamically evaluates oral and pharyngeal phases of swallowing and identifies aspiration risk.<br><br>It is especially valuable in neurological dysphagia and postoperative swallowing rehabilitation planning.<br><br>Audiometry (C) and vestibular testing (D) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve lies in close relation to the:",o:["Mastoid antrum","Tracheoesophageal groove","External auditory canal","Orbit","Maxillary sinus"],a:1,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove before entering the larynx.<br><br>Esophageal tumors and thyroid surgery may therefore cause recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy with resulting hoarseness.<br><br>The mastoid antrum (A) and orbit (D) are unrelated structures.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing reflux disease develops posterior commissure hypertrophy. This finding is most consistent with:",o:["Laryngopharyngeal reflux","Bell palsy","Otitis externa","Ménière disease","Acute mastoiditis"],a:0,e:"Chronic exposure of laryngeal mucosa to gastric contents causes edema and hypertrophy of posterior laryngeal structures.<br><br>Persistent throat clearing, globus sensation, and hoarseness are common associated symptoms.<br><br>Otitis externa (C) and mastoiditis (E) are unrelated ENT disorders.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and aspiration secondary to Zenker diverticulum most commonly aspirates because of:",o:["Regurgitation of retained pouch contents","Middle ear disease","Cochlear dysfunction","Facial nerve paralysis","Nasal obstruction"],a:0,e:"Food retained within the diverticular pouch may regurgitate into the pharynx and spill into the airway, particularly during recumbency.<br><br>This explains recurrent nocturnal aspiration and chronic chest infections in advanced disease.<br><br>Facial paralysis (D) and nasal obstruction (E) are unrelated mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops cervical emphysema and fever after esophageal instrumentation. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Esophageal perforation","Bell palsy","Acute sinusitis","Cholesteatoma","Otosclerosis"],a:0,e:"Esophageal perforation allows air and saliva to escape into cervical fascial planes, producing emphysema, pain, and potentially mediastinitis.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis significantly increases mortality and morbidity.<br><br>Otosclerosis (E) and cholesteatoma (D) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia but normal endoscopy and imaging most likely has:",o:["Globus pharyngeus","Acute mastoiditis","Bell palsy","Ménière disease","Nasal polyposis"],a:0,e:"Globus pharyngeus causes persistent throat lump sensation without structural obstruction or true progressive dysphagia.<br><br>Symptoms are often intermittent and associated with stress or reflux disease.<br><br>Bell palsy (C) and mastoiditis (B) do not produce isolated globus sensation.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe esophageal stricture following corrosive ingestion is most likely to require:",o:["Serial dilatation procedures","Mastoidectomy","Tympanoplasty","Septoplasty","Cochlear implantation"],a:0,e:"Fibrotic strictures after corrosive injury frequently require repeated endoscopic dilatation to restore esophageal patency and improve swallowing.<br><br>Severe or refractory disease may eventually require reconstructive surgery.<br><br>Mastoidectomy (B) and cochlear implantation (E) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Plummer-Vinson syndrome usually develops dysphagia because of:",o:["Upper esophageal web formation","Lower esophageal sphincter spasm","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Nasal obstruction","Middle ear disease"],a:0,e:"Upper esophageal webs partially obstruct the cervical esophagus and cause slowly progressive dysphagia, especially for solids.<br><br>Iron supplementation improves symptoms in many patients, although some require endoscopic dilatation for persistent obstruction.<br><br>Lower esophageal sphincter spasm (B) is characteristic of achalasia rather than Plummer-Vinson syndrome.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and weight loss undergoes barium swallow showing irregular narrowing of the upper esophagus. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Achalasia cardia","Diffuse esophageal spasm","Zenker diverticulum","Esophageal web","Upper esophageal carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Irregular narrowing with shouldering on barium swallow strongly suggests malignant esophageal obstruction. Progressive dysphagia and constitutional symptoms further support the diagnosis.<br><br>ENT evaluation should include direct endoscopy with biopsy and imaging for staging because recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement may coexist.<br><br>Achalasia (A) typically demonstrates smooth tapering rather than irregular narrowing.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia develops recurrent chest infections due to aspiration. Which protective mechanism normally prevents aspiration during swallowing?",o:["Vocal cord abduction","Tongue protrusion","Eustachian tube opening","Nasal septal movement","Glottic closure with laryngeal elevation"],a:4,e:"During normal swallowing, the larynx elevates and the vocal cords adduct tightly to protect the airway from aspiration.<br><br>Failure of this coordinated mechanism in neurological or structural disorders predisposes patients to aspiration pneumonia and chronic cough.<br><br>Vocal cord abduction (A) widens the airway and would increase aspiration risk.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and severe retrosternal pain undergoes endoscopy revealing multiple esophageal ulcers after prolonged doxycycline use. Which condition is most likely?",o:["Zenker diverticulum","Achalasia","Pill-induced esophagitis","Esophageal varices","Globus pharyngeus"],a:2,e:"Certain medications including doxycycline may lodge transiently in the esophagus and cause direct mucosal injury leading to ulceration and odynophagia.<br><br>Patients usually present with acute painful swallowing and retrosternal discomfort rather than progressive obstruction.<br><br>Zenker diverticulum (C) causes regurgitation and aspiration rather than acute ulcerative pain.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding reflux disease develops Barrett esophagus. The major concern in such patients is increased risk of:",o:["Squamous papilloma","Adenocarcinoma","Vocal cord nodules","Acute epiglottitis","Bell palsy"],a:1,e:"Barrett esophagus involves intestinal metaplasia of distal esophageal mucosa secondary to chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease.<br><br>This condition significantly increases risk of esophageal adenocarcinoma and therefore requires surveillance endoscopy in selected patients.<br><br>Vocal cord nodules (C) and Bell palsy (E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia and gurgling neck swelling most likely has:",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Esophageal varices","Retropharyngeal abscess","Laryngeal papillomatosis","Zenker diverticulum"],a:4,e:"Zenker diverticulum commonly presents with dysphagia, regurgitation, aspiration, halitosis, and a characteristic gurgling sensation in the neck during swallowing.<br><br>Food retention within the pouch explains the chronicity and aspiration symptoms.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (C) typically presents with fever, toxicity, and acute airway symptoms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with corrosive esophageal stricture fails repeated dilatation therapy. Which surgical option may ultimately be required?",o:["Cochlear implantation","Mastoidectomy","Tympanoplasty","Septoplasty","Esophageal replacement surgery"],a:4,e:"Severe refractory corrosive strictures may eventually require reconstructive procedures such as gastric pull-up or colonic interposition.<br><br>Nutritional compromise and recurrent aspiration are common indications for definitive surgical reconstruction.<br><br>Cochlear implantation (A) and mastoidectomy (E) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe odynophagia and chest pain after endoscopy develops tachycardia and fever. Which diagnosis should be suspected first?",o:["Acute mastoiditis","Acute sinusitis","Bell palsy","Otosclerosis","Esophageal perforation"],a:4,e:"Perforation following instrumentation causes leakage of saliva and bacteria into cervical and mediastinal spaces, rapidly producing systemic toxicity.<br><br>Fever, severe pain, crepitus, and tachycardia after endoscopy should always raise suspicion for perforation.<br><br>Bell palsy (C) and otosclerosis (D) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with postcricoid carcinoma most likely develops anemia because of:",o:["Vitamin B12 deficiency only","Acute hemolysis","Excess erythropoietin","Polycythemia","Chronic occult blood loss and nutritional deficiency"],a:4,e:"Postcricoid carcinoma commonly causes nutritional compromise and chronic mucosal blood loss, resulting in iron deficiency anemia.<br><br>The association between iron deficiency and postcricoid malignancy is especially emphasized in ENT examinations.<br><br>Polycythemia (D) and acute hemolysis (E) are not characteristic findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and recurrent aspiration undergoes flexible endoscopic evaluation of swallowing (FEES). The major advantage of FEES is:",o:["Evaluation of cochlear function","Evaluation of sinus drainage","Measurement of vestibular reflexes","Assessment of middle ear pressure","Direct bedside visualization of aspiration"],a:4,e:"FEES permits real-time bedside assessment of secretion pooling, penetration, aspiration, and pharyngeal residue during swallowing.<br><br>It is especially useful in critically ill or neurologically impaired patients who cannot undergo fluoroscopic studies easily.<br><br>Vestibular reflexes (C) and middle ear pressure (D) are unrelated assessments.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia develops hoarseness due to involvement of the recurrent laryngeal nerve. The left recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the:",o:["Subclavian artery","Arch of aorta","Common carotid artery","Internal jugular vein","Pulmonary vein"],a:1,e:"The left recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the arch of the aorta before ascending within the tracheoesophageal groove toward the larynx.<br><br>Thoracic esophageal tumors may therefore involve the nerve and produce unilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>The right recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the subclavian artery rather than the aortic arch.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with achalasia cardia demonstrates which classic radiological sign on barium swallow?",o:["Apple-core lesion","Bird-beak appearance","Double bubble sign","Thumb sign","String sign"],a:1,e:"Achalasia produces smooth tapering narrowing at the lower esophageal sphincter, classically described as a bird-beak appearance on barium swallow.<br><br>Associated findings include proximal esophageal dilatation and delayed passage of contrast material.<br><br>Apple-core lesion (A) is more suggestive of malignant esophageal narrowing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe reflux disease complains mainly of chronic cough and throat clearing rather than heartburn. Which diagnosis best explains this presentation?",o:["Ménière disease","Nasal polyposis","Acute epiglottitis","Bell palsy","Laryngopharyngeal reflux"],a:4,e:"Laryngopharyngeal reflux frequently presents with extraesophageal manifestations including chronic cough, globus sensation, throat clearing, and hoarseness.<br><br>Many patients lack typical gastroesophageal reflux symptoms such as heartburn.<br><br>Ménière disease (A) and Bell palsy (D) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced esophageal carcinoma develops severe dysphagia and cachexia. Which feeding procedure is commonly performed for nutritional support?",o:["Tympanoplasty","Cochlear implantation","Mastoidectomy","Septoplasty","Feeding gastrostomy"],a:4,e:"Advanced obstructive esophageal malignancy may prevent adequate oral intake, requiring enteral nutritional support through feeding gastrostomy or jejunostomy.<br><br>Improved nutritional status is important before definitive oncologic therapy whenever possible.<br><br>Tympanoplasty (A) and mastoidectomy (C) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diffuse esophageal spasm most commonly presents with:",o:["Chest pain and intermittent dysphagia","Severe epistaxis","Conductive hearing loss","Facial paralysis","Acute vertigo"],a:0,e:"Diffuse esophageal spasm causes uncoordinated esophageal contractions resulting in intermittent dysphagia and chest pain that may mimic cardiac disease.<br><br>Symptoms are often episodic and may worsen with stress or temperature extremes in food intake.<br><br>Vertigo (E) and hearing loss (C) are unrelated manifestations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after anterior cervical spine surgery most likely developed symptoms because the cervical esophagus is:",o:["Completely intrathoracic","Within carotid sheath","Lateral to sternocleidomastoid only","Posterior to vertebral bodies","Closely related to cervical vertebrae"],a:4,e:"The cervical esophagus lies directly anterior to the cervical vertebral column and may be retracted or injured during anterior cervical spine procedures.<br><br>Transient postoperative dysphagia is therefore relatively common after such operations.<br><br>The esophagus is not located within the carotid sheath.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with esophageal disorder complains of painful swallowing. Which term correctly describes this symptom?",o:["Dysphonia","Rhinolalia","Dysarthria","Aphonia","Odynophagia"],a:4,e:"Odynophagia specifically refers to pain during swallowing and commonly occurs in inflammatory, infective, or malignant esophageal disorders.<br><br>It differs from dysphagia, which describes difficulty in swallowing rather than pain itself.<br><br>Aphonia (D) refers to complete loss of voice.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia and aspiration secondary to neurological disease may ultimately require:",o:["Tracheostomy or airway diversion procedure","Septoplasty","Tympanoplasty","Cochlear implantation","Mastoid exploration"],a:0,e:"Severe neurogenic aspiration refractory to rehabilitation may necessitate airway protection procedures including tracheostomy or laryngotracheal separation.<br><br>These interventions aim to reduce recurrent aspiration pneumonia and improve long-term survival.<br><br>Septoplasty (B) and cochlear implantation (D) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent aspiration and regurgitation is found to have a pharyngoesophageal pouch. Which age group is most commonly affected?",o:["Neonates","Young adults only","Adolescents only","Infants exclusively","Elderly patients"],a:4,e:"Zenker diverticulum occurs predominantly in elderly individuals because of age-related dysfunction of the cricopharyngeus muscle and upper esophageal sphincter.<br><br>Symptoms often progress gradually over years before diagnosis is established.<br><br>The condition is uncommon in neonates and young adults.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding achalasia is at increased risk of developing:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma of esophagus","Bell palsy","Ménière disease","Cholesteatoma","Otitis externa"],a:0,e:"Chronic stasis of food and inflammation within the esophagus in achalasia predispose patients to squamous cell carcinoma over time.<br><br>Long-term surveillance may therefore be considered in selected longstanding cases.<br><br>Ménière disease (C) and Bell palsy (B) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia develops nasal regurgitation during swallowing. Which cranial nerve dysfunction is most likely involved?",o:["Optic nerve","Oculomotor nerve","Facial nerve only","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Glossopharyngeal and vagus nerves"],a:4,e:"Palatal and pharyngeal weakness due to glossopharyngeal and vagal dysfunction impairs closure of the nasopharynx during swallowing.<br><br>This results in nasal regurgitation and aspiration, particularly in bulbar palsy and skull base lesions.<br><br>Optic (A) and oculomotor nerves (E) are unrelated to swallowing physiology.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysphagia after radiotherapy most commonly develops which late complication?",o:["Fibrotic stricture formation","Acute otitis externa","Facial palsy","Cholesteatoma","Vestibular neuritis"],a:0,e:"Radiotherapy may produce progressive fibrosis and narrowing of the pharyngoesophageal segment, resulting in delayed dysphagia and aspiration.<br><br>Endoscopic dilatation may be required repeatedly in severe strictures.<br><br>Cholesteatoma (D) and vestibular neuritis (E) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with upper esophageal malignancy develops stridor. This finding usually indicates:",o:["Early localized disease","Conductive hearing loss","Ménière disease","Bell palsy","Airway involvement or recurrent nerve palsy"],a:4,e:"Stridor in esophageal or hypopharyngeal malignancy suggests advanced disease with airway compromise from laryngeal invasion or bilateral vocal cord dysfunction.<br><br>Urgent airway assessment and possible tracheostomy may become necessary.<br><br>Conductive hearing loss (E) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with dysphagia and severe retrosternal burning most likely suffers from:",o:["Gastroesophageal reflux disease","Acute mastoiditis","Bell palsy","Ménière disease","Otitis externa"],a:0,e:"Gastroesophageal reflux disease commonly presents with heartburn, retrosternal burning, regurgitation, and sometimes dysphagia due to inflammation or stricture formation.<br><br>ENT manifestations may include chronic cough, hoarseness, and laryngopharyngeal reflux symptoms.<br><br>Ménière disease (D) and Bell palsy (C) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe aspiration due to cricopharyngeal dysfunction may benefit from:",o:["Cricopharyngeal myotomy","Septoplasty","Tympanoplasty","Mastoidectomy","Cochlear implantation"],a:0,e:"Cricopharyngeal myotomy relieves upper esophageal sphincter dysfunction by dividing the cricopharyngeus muscle and improving bolus passage.<br><br>Selected patients experience significant reduction in aspiration and dysphagia after surgery.<br><br>Septoplasty (B) and mastoidectomy (D) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysphagia and weight loss undergoes endoscopy. The major advantage of endoscopy over barium swallow is:",o:["Visualization of mastoid air cells","Ability to obtain biopsy","Evaluation of vestibular reflexes","Assessment of middle ear pressure","Measurement of cochlear function"],a:1,e:"Endoscopy allows direct visualization and histopathological sampling of suspicious lesions, making it essential in evaluation of suspected malignancy.<br><br>Barium swallow may demonstrate structural abnormalities but cannot establish definitive tissue diagnosis.<br><br>Vestibular reflexes (C) and middle ear pressure (D) are unrelated evaluations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
];